S-Q-S: the queue, standard versus FIFO.

S-Q-S is a fully managed message queue. A producer calls send-message, and the message sits in the queue. A consumer calls receive-message, gets back up to ten messages, does its work, and then calls delete-message to remove each one. If the consumer never deletes, because it crashed, timed out, or threw an error, the message reappears in the queue after the visibility timeout, and another consumer picks it up. That reappearance is the heart of S-Q-S's at-least-once guarantee. While a message is being processed, it's hidden from other consumers, so two workers don't both run the same job; a consumer can extend the timeout with change-message-visibility if the work turns out to take longer. Messages are up to two hundred fifty-six kilobytes, and retained for up to fourteen days.

There are two flavours, and the choice is almost always driven by ordering. Standard gives best-effort ordering and at-least-once delivery, with occasional duplicates, but effectively unlimited throughput. Most asynchronous work fits here: image processing, email sending, log shipping. The one requirement is that the consumer must be idempotent, meaning it can process the same message twice without corrupting state, which is good design anyway. FIFO trades throughput for strict ordering per message group and exactly-once processing, at about three hundred messages a second, or three thousand with batching, and the queue name must end in dot-fifo. It comes with two concepts: a Message Group I-D, where messages sharing a group are delivered in strict order while different groups run in parallel; and a deduplication I-D, which drops duplicates within a five-minute window.

The default is Standard with idempotent consumers; reach for FIFO only when ordering or exactly-once genuinely matters.
